Introduction

The global objective of this assignment is to analyze the education outcomes in one county in the Bay Area. I personally chose to analyze the education outcomes in the San Francisco county. To do that I will:

  1. Plot a bar chart showing the San Francisco county educational attainment by race (proportion of each race in every category of educational attainment), then compare it with a bar chart showing the global Bay Area educational attainment by race
  2. Display a map showing an estimate of the number and percentage of K-12 students who have no internet access at home in the San Francisco county and the same map for the whole Bay Area, and discuss on potential patterns
  3. Analyze the migration in the San Francisco county using a flow table and comment on the potential sources of educational mobility

You may show or hide the code chunks by clicking on the Code buttons on the right of the document.

Educational attainment by race

For my educational outcomes in the San Francisco county analysis, I will first comment on the relations between race and educational attainment in the county and compare it with the situation in the Bay Area.

In San Francisco county

First, let’s extract the data from the American Community Survey (ACS) Census Bureau. I will use the data from 2018 and the 5 years before stocked using the ID C15002 . As I am only interested in the San Francisco county, I will only extract data from region = "county:075", regionin = "state:06".

Sys.setenv(CENSUS_KEY="c8aa67e4086b4b5ce3a8717f59faa9a28f611dab")

acs_vars_2018_5yr <-
  listCensusMetadata(
    name = "2018/acs/acs5",
    type = "variables"
  )

census_race_labels <-
  c(
    "White Alone",
    "Black or African American",
    "American Indian and Alaska Native Alone",
    "Asian Alone",
    "Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Alone",
    "Some Other Race Alone",
    "Two or More Races"
  )

sf_educ_race <-
  1:7 %>% 
  map_dfr(function(x){
    getCensus(
      name = "acs/acs5",
      vintage = 2018,
      region = "county:075",
      regionin = "state:06",
      vars = paste0("group(C15002",LETTERS[x],")")
    ) %>%
      select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
      pivot_longer(
        ends_with("E"),
        names_to = "variable",
        values_to = "estimate"
      ) %>%
      left_join(
        acs_vars_2018_5yr %>% 
          select(name, label), 
        by = c("variable" = "name")
      ) %>% 
      select(-variable) %>% 
      separate(
        label,
        into = c(NA,NA,'SEX','EDUCATION'),
        sep = "!!"
      ) %>% 
      filter(!is.na(EDUCATION)) %>% 
      mutate(race = census_race_labels[x])%>%
      select(
        !c(county,SEX)
      )
  })

I can now plot the total number of each race in every category of educational attainment within the county as a bar chart. Because the x-axis labels are long character strings, I flip the axes using the coord_flip() function to better visualize the data:

sf_educ_total <-
  sf_educ_race %>% 
  group_by(race) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
  mutate(EDUCATION = "Total")

saveRDS(sf_educ_total,'sf_educ_total.rds')

sf_educ_race %>% 
  group_by(EDUCATION, race) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
  rbind(sf_educ_total) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(
    aes(
      x = EDUCATION %>% factor(levels = rev(c("Total",sf_educ_race$EDUCATION[1:4]))),
      y = estimate,
      fill = race
    ),
    stat = "identity",
    position = "stack"
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Educational attainment",
    y = "Population in the category",
    title = "San Francisco county educational attainment by race",
    fill = "Race"
  ) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.direction = "vertical"
  ) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="RdYlGn")

This graph shows that the global education attainment among the San Francisco is very high: more than half the population has a Bachelor’s degree or higher. I can notice the following trends at first sight:

  • The White Alone population is much overrepresented among the Bachelor’s degree or higher category and underrepresented in the lower categories, especially Less than high school diploma and High school graduate (includes equivalency)
  • The Asian alone population seems to be unequally distributed among the different categories, with an overrepresentation among the Less than high school diploma education attainment
  • The Two or More Races population seems to be mostly represented in the Bachelor’s degree or higher category, and Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Alone people equally distributed among the High school graduate (includes equivalency), Some college or associate’s degree and Bachelor’s degree or higher categories

However, this graph representation is not adapted to get more details on the actual repartition of races among the educational attainment categories. Therefore, I will plot a filled bar chart using the position = "fill" argument to get information on the proportion of each race in every category instead of the total numbers.

sf_educ_race %>% 
  group_by(EDUCATION, race) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
  rbind(sf_educ_total) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(
    aes(
      x = EDUCATION %>% factor(levels = rev(c("Total",sf_educ_race$EDUCATION[1:4]))),
      y = estimate,
      fill = race
    ),
    stat = "identity",
    position = "fill"
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Educational attainment",
    y = "Proportion of the category",
    title = "San Francisco county educational attainment by race",
    fill = "Race"
  ) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.direction = "vertical"
  ) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="RdYlGn")

Let’s first have a look at the total proportion of each race in the San Francisco county educational system. Almost 50% are part of the White Alone race and nearly 30% of the Asian Alone. The Two or More Races category represents approximately 7% of the total, 6% and 4% for the Black or African American and Some Other Race Alone categories. The American Indian and Alaska Native Alone and Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Alone categories are almost unrepresented. I will now review the evolution of this repartition for each type of educational attainment.

The White Alone and Asian Alone categories proportions have two opposite trends: the White Alone category proportion increases with the education attainment while the Asian Alone race proportion decreases. Compared to the global San Francisco county repartition, the White Alone category is much underrepresented in the educational attainment categories lower than Some college or associate’s degree, while the Asian Alone race is much overrepresented. The proportions of these two categories is the closest one to the total for the Some college or associate’s degree educational attainment. However, the balance is flipped for the Bachelor’s degree or higher level: the White Alone category is now overrepresented and the Asian Alone are underrepresented.

The Some Other Race Alone and Black or African American categories proportions have a same evolution for an educational attainment higher than Less than high school diploma: an overrepresentation in the High school graduate (includes equivalency) and Some college or associate’s degree levels, but a severe underrepresentation for the Bachelor’s degree or higher educational attainment (especially for the Black or African American population). I can also notice a much higher proportion of the Some Other Race Alone category among the Less than high school diploma educational attainment compared to its global proportion among the San Francisco county population.

As for the Two or More Races category, its representation compared to the global San Francisco county is: slightly lower in the Less than high school diploma level, roughly equal for the High school graduate (includes equivalency) and Bachelor’s degree or higher levels, slightly higher for the Some college or associate’s degree level.

Because of their very low proportions among the total population of the county, it is hard to raise trends for the American Indian and Alaska Native Alone and Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Alone categories. From the bar chart representation, I assume that the proportion of Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Alone is quite representative for every educational attainment. I assume the same for the American Indian and Alaska Native Alone, except for the Bachelor’s degree or higher level because this population seems to be unrepresented.

I first notice that the Asian Alone category proportion is smaller among the Bay Area population than it is in the San Francisco county, while the White Alone, Some Other Race Alone and Black or African American categories proportions are slightly higher.

Compared to the San Francisco county’s educational attainment repartition, the White Alone and Some Other Race Alone categories proportions are much more important in the Less than high school diploma educational attainment, while the Asian Alone category is much less represented and Black or African American slightly less. However, these two last categories proportions in this educational attainment are roughly equivalent to their global proportion among the Bay Area educational system, while the White Alone category proportion is very low and the Some Other Race Alone proportion is very high.

In the High school graduate educational attainment, I observe the same patterns for the White Alone and Asian Alone categories proportions compared to the San Francisco county’s repartition. The Some Other Race Alone category proportion is still slightly disproportionate, and the Black or African American population proportion is also a bit higher than the global one. It is interesting to raise that the Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Alone category proportion is much higher compared to their global proportion in the Bay Area.

The Some college or associate’s degree educational attainment shows the closest repartition to the Bay Area’s. The only noticeable differences are the slightly higher proportions of the Two or More Races and Black or African American categories and the much lower proportion of the Asian Alone category. Finally, the Bachelor’s degree or higher shows the closest repartition to the San Francisco county’s in the Bay Area. Compared to the repartition in the Bay, this educational attainment is the closest one. The only observable dissimilarities is the higher proportion of the Asian Alone category and the slightly lower proportions of the Some Other Race Alone and Black or African American categories.

Conclusion on educational attainment

Before stating any conclusion, it is important to mention that the universe of the ACS datasets on educational attainment is “population 25 years or older”. Therefore, all the population 25 years or younger is not represented in these analysis. Part of it might be part - or is part when it comes to the Less than high school diploma - of the San Francisco county/Bay Area educational system. This is why the following assumptions may be proven wrong in the coming years depending on the evolution of the social diversity and inequities.

The San Francisco county shows a much more unequal educational attainment by race than the global Bay Area. The bar chart is much less centered and shows a linear variation instead; the White Alone race has a much higher educational attainment compared to the Some Other Race Alone and Black or African American categories while the Asian Alone category is less and less represented when the level of education increases. This same underrepresentation of the Some Other Race Alone and Black or African American populations among the highest educational attainment can be observed in the whole Bay Area, but the White Alone race representation is closest to its actual proportion of the population and the Asian Alone is a bit overrepresented, which is an indicator of social inclusion.

K-12 students who have no internet access at home

The next step of my analysis consists in reviewing the impact of housing location and the ability to access internet for K-12 students (from kindergarten to 12th grade). Having an internet access is essential to a proper learning, especially during the COVID-19 pandemic because remote learning has become necessary.

Even in usual circumstances, an internet access at home is even more for young students. First, because it is the first source of information available and some assignments might be asked to be worked on or sent via internet, but also because they might not have the opportunity to find a free public internet access outside home (cafes, libraries…) for safety or mobility reasons.

In San Francisco county

Let’s first plot the map of the percentage of K-12 students with no internet access at home in the San Francisco county. I used the get_pums() function to extract the PUMS files from the 2019-1yr ACS:

census_api_key("c8aa67e4086b4b5ce3a8717f59faa9a28f611dab")
ca_pums <- get_pums(
  variables = c(
    "PUMA",
    "NP",
    "SCHG",
    "ACCESS"
  ),
  state = "CA",
  year = 2019,
  survey = "acs1",
  recode = T
)

Using the PUMS Data dictionnary, I can then identify and merge the K-12 students with no internet access at home according to their PUMA codes, then plot the map using the leaflet() function. To be able to display both the percentages and numbers of K-12 students, I created my own label SF_label using the sprintf() and lapply(htmltools::HTML) functions:

ca_pumas <-
  pumas("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F)

ca_counties <- counties("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F)
SF_county_names <-
  c(
    "San Francisco"
  )
SF_counties <-
  ca_counties %>%
  filter(NAME %in% SF_county_names)

ca_cities <- places("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = FALSE)
SF_cities <- ca_cities[SF_counties, ]
SF_cities_within <-
  ca_cities %>%
  st_centroid() %>%
  .[SF_counties, ] %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  left_join(ca_cities %>% select(GEOID)) %>%
  st_as_sf()

SF_cities_within <-
  ca_cities[which(ca_cities$GEOID %in% st_centroid(ca_cities)[SF_counties, ]$GEOID), ]

usa_zips <-
  zctas(cb = T, progress_bar = F)

SF_zips <-
  usa_zips %>%
  st_centroid() %>%
  .[SF_counties, ] %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  left_join(usa_zips %>% select(GEOID10)) %>%
  st_as_sf()


SF_pumas <-
  ca_pumas %>%
  st_centroid() %>%
  .[SF_counties, ] %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  left_join(ca_pumas %>% select(GEOID10)) %>%
  st_as_sf()

SF_pumas$PUMACE10<-as.numeric(SF_pumas$PUMACE10)

SF_pums <-
  ca_pums %>%
  filter(PUMA %in% SF_pumas$PUMACE10)

SF_pums$PUMA<-as.numeric(SF_pums$PUMA)

SF_pums_K12_nointernet <-
  SF_pums %>%
  mutate(
    K12_nointernet = ifelse(
        (ACCESS == 3) &
        (SCHG %in% 2:14),
      PWGTP,
      0
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(PUMA) %>%
  summarize(
    K12_nointernet_per =
      sum(K12_nointernet*as.numeric(SPORDER), na.rm =T)/sum(PWGTP, na.rm = T)*100,
    K12_nointernet_tot = sum(K12_nointernet, na.rm =T),
    K12_tot = (K12_nointernet_tot*100)/K12_nointernet_per
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    SF_pumas %>%
      select(PUMACE10),
    by = c("PUMA" = "PUMACE10")
  ) %>%
  st_as_sf()

SF_pums_pal_per <- colorNumeric(
  palette = "YlOrRd",
  domain = SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_nointernet_per
)

SF_labels_per <- sprintf(
  "<strong>%s%%</strong><br/>%g students",
  round(SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_nointernet_per, digits = 2), SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_nointernet_tot
) %>% lapply(htmltools::HTML)

leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addPolygons(
    data = SF_pums_K12_nointernet,
    fillColor = ~SF_pums_pal_per(K12_nointernet_per),
    color = "white",
    opacity = 0.7,
    fillOpacity = 0.7,
    weight = 1,
    label = SF_labels_per,
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 1
    )
  ) %>%
  addLegend(
    data = SF_pums_K12_nointernet,
    pal = SF_pums_pal_per,
    values = ~K12_nointernet_per,
    title = "% K-12 students<br>no internet access<br>at home"
  )

For the following comments, I will define the San Francisco county’s geography as follows:

  • Middle (Mid) SF: Le Castro, Bernal Heights and Haight-Ashbury
  • South-East (S-E) SF: Portola, Hunters Point, Visitacion Valley and Excelsior District
  • South-West (S-W) SF: Merced and Westwood areas
  • West (W) SF: Sunset District and Forest Hill
  • North-West (N-W) SF: Richmond District
  • North-East (N-E) SF: Financial District, North Beach and Treasure Island
  • East (E) SF: Mission District and Dogpatch

I observe three different patterns: in the W, S-W and Mid SF, all K-12 students have an internet access at home. In the top part of the county (N-W, N-E and E SF), a majority of K-12 students have an internet access at home, but there is nonetheless 269 students not benefiting from it in this area. The S-E SF clearly stands out from the other counties. The map shows a much higher percentage of K-12 students with no internet access at home (2.54%) than the other areas.

I find it interesting to put these numbers in perspective with the total number of K-12 students in each part of the county to have a real perspective on the issue. In my opinion, using the percentage data is not adapted to the San Francisco county because he is much smaller than the other counties in the Bay. Therefore, the surface covered by one of its section is also much smaller than in the others. Analyzing percentages is relevant when there is a huge difference in student populations between the sections of a county due to the concentration of educational institutions, because it takes into account the concentration of student population in a defined area. Here, the areas borders are so closed to each other that a K-12 student might be studying in another section than the one he is living in. A quick argument is that if 61 students represent 0.12% of the N-W SF K-12 student population, then the 618 students with no internet access at home in the S-E SF would have represented only 1.21% of the N-W SF K-12 student population, when it represents more than 2.5% in the S-E area.

It makes me think that this is in fact a problem of neighborhood inequalities that leads to inequalities in education. This is why I chose to plot the same map but using the total number of K-12 students with no internet access at home as scale instead of the percentage to support my idea:

SF_pums_pal_tot <- colorNumeric(
  palette = "YlOrRd",
  domain = SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_nointernet_tot
)

SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_tot[is.nan(SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_tot)]<-0

SF_labels_tot <- sprintf(
  "<strong>%s out of %s students</strong>",
  SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_nointernet_tot,round(SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_tot, digits=0), round(SF_pums_K12_nointernet$K12_nointernet_per, digits = 2)
) %>% lapply(htmltools::HTML)

leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addPolygons(
    data = SF_pums_K12_nointernet,
    fillColor = ~SF_pums_pal_tot(K12_nointernet_tot),
    color = "white",
    opacity = 0.7,
    fillOpacity = 0.7,
    weight = 1,
    label = SF_labels_tot,
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 1
    )
  ) %>%
  addLegend(
    data = SF_pums_K12_nointernet,
    pal = SF_pums_pal_tot,
    values = ~K12_nointernet_tot,
    title = "Number of K-12 students<br>no internet access<br>at home"
  )

I think this map allows to better visualize the differences and inequalities among the different areas of the county. In fact, the top part of the county clearly stands out from the W/S-W/Mid part of the county. The S-E part of SF still appears to have much more K-12 students with no internet access at home than the others.

To conclude, I wanted to highlight through the specific study of the San Francisco county that the inequalities in the access to education (here symbolized by an internet access at home) are directly related to neighborhood inequalities. According to the Bloomberg CityLab, these consist in “the juxtaposition of concentrated disadvantage and concentrated advantage at the extremes”. Here, the S-E SF clearly suffers from these inequalities, and the K-12 students living in this area might be impacted in their ability to pursue higher level studies, or even succeed in the on they are enrolled in.

This is why I will isolate the Alameda county for a dedicated part and will analyze the global Bay without this county instead. In fact, the very high percentage (13.93%) does not allow a porper visualization of the contrasts among the other counties/regions.

The map now reveals much more about the inequalities in internet access at home for K-12 students in the Bay. In fact, I can notice three patterns:

  • The suburban areas of big cities are much unprivileged compared to the center. San Jose clearly pictures this phenomenon: the center of the city has no K-12 students with no internet access at home, while the suburbs regroup more than 3000 unprivileged K-12 students.
  • Poorer cities adjacent to very rich cities also show high percentages. For example, Redwood City and San Carlos have much higher numbers than Palo Alto and Mountain View. Additionally, it could be interesting to have more insight of the local repartition of these students. In fact, North Palo Alto has a high percentage, but I would like to be able to know if the students with no internet access at home live close to the border with Redwood City or not. San Rafael also have very high percentages compared to North San Francisco and Richmond.
  • Cities far from the economical center of the Bay are also much unprivileged. The cities of Vacaville, Dixon, Santa Rosa, Morgan Hill et Gilroy clearly highlight this phenomenon.

These patterns raise the issue of a vicious circle when it comes to inequalities among cities: the richer a city gets (in terms of job opportunities and economic activity), the better the offer for education is (because the infrastructures are adapted accordingly), the more expensive the housing becomes (because of the elevation of living standards), and eventually the city becomes even richer.

However, as I mentioned before, the Alameda county clearly shows very high percentages while none of these patterns seem to be applicable here. This is why I will further analyze the case of Alameda county in the following part in order to put it in perspective with the results obtained for the San Francisco county.

Conclusion on housing location and the ability to access internet for K-12 students

This in-depth analysis of the repartition of K-12 students with no internet access at home allowed me to consider reoccurring patterns on different scales:

  • At city level, the San Francisco county proves that there can be huge differences in internet access availability between two adjacent neighborhoods
  • At county level, cities such as Oakland shows that a single city can regroup a huge part of all the K-12 students with no internet access at home
  • At the Bay Area level, most of the K-12 students with no internet access at home are regrouped in counties/cities accordingly to very precise criteria: distance from the center of the city, distance from another rich city and distance from the economical center of the Bay.

Overall, the number of K-12 students with no internet access at home therefore appears to be a good indicator of social inequality among a population and a defined area; an internet access is essential to succeed in or even attend an academic curriculum, especially during the COVID-19 pandemic. While it was an incredible tool to get help or information, internet is now vital to be able to follow remote lessons, especially synchronous ones. Unfortunately, the highest percentages in the previous analyses occurred in the poorest areas of the Bay, which constitutes a vicious circle: children from poorest families don’t have all the tools required to properly follow their lessons, and therefore have lower chances to get a high educational attainment. It becomes then even more difficult for them to access higher incomes jobs.

Combining this indicator with the one studied in the first part (educational attainment by race), we could make some assumptions on the number of students with no internet at home by race, or even the repartition of different races among the areas of the county. For instance, it would be interesting to see if Some Other Race Alone and Black or African American categories have proportionally a higher rate of no internet access at home, if they live in higher proportions in the E SF, and to what extent it could explain their severe underrepresentation for the Bachelor’s degree or higher educational attainment.

Educational mobility

The final step of my analysis consists in analyzing the educational mobility by educational attainment in the San Francisco county. Because I spent some time commenting on the Alameda county’s situation in my previous part, I will do the same here to see if I can see significant results. I will also compare the results with a county that showed very low percentages and numbers of students with no internet access at home (Solano County).

In San Francisco county

Let’s create a table regrouping the data from the American Community Survey (ACS 2019-1yr and ACS 2018-5yr) Census Bureau related to the educational mobility by educational attainment (ID B07009). I use the following definitions for the variables I will plot and analyze:

  • Internal net: Educational mobility from inside the county.
    • A positive Internal net for a certain educational attainment could mean that people within the county have increased their education level (got a degree, graduated…), or a higher number of answers to the ACS between 2019 and the previous years.
    • A negative Internal net should be the consequence of a positive one and the two should balance (except for unusual cases such as deceases).
  • External net: Educational mobility coming from outside the county.
    • A positive External net for a certain educational attainment means that people with this level of education have settled in the county.
    • A negative External net for a certain educational attainment means that people with this level of education have left in the county.
library(tidyverse)
library(censusapi)

Sys.setenv(CENSUS_KEY="c8aa67e4086b4b5ce3a8717f59faa9a28f611dab")

acs_vars_2019_1yr <-
  listCensusMetadata(
    name = "2019/acs/acs1",
    type = "variables"
  )

sf_mobility_educ_current_19 <- 
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2019,
    region = "county:075",
    regionin = "state:06",
    vars = c("group(B07009)")
  ) %>% 
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>% 
      select(name, label), 
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>%
  select(-variable) %>%
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"mobility","education"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    mobility = ifelse(
      mobility %in% c("Same house 1 year ago:", "Moved within same county:"),
      "Here since last year",
      "Inflow"
    )
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(education)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, education) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))


sf_mobility_educ_lastyear_19 <-
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2019,
    region = "county:075",
    regionin = "state:06",
    vars = c("group(B07409)")
  ) %>%
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>%
      select(name, label),
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>%
  select(-variable) %>%
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"mobility","education"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    mobility = ifelse(
      mobility %in% c("Same house:", "Moved within same county:"),
      "Here since last year",
      "Outflow"
    )
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(education)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, education) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))


sf_mobility_educ_current_18 <-
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "county:075",
    regionin = "state:06",
    vars = c("group(B07009)")
  ) %>%
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>%
      select(name, label),
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>%
  select(-variable) %>%
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"mobility","education"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    mobility = "Here last year"
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(education)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, education) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))

sf_flows_19 <-
  rbind(
    sf_mobility_educ_current_18,
    sf_mobility_educ_lastyear_19 %>%
      filter(mobility == "Outflow"),
    sf_mobility_educ_current_19 %>%
      filter(mobility == "Inflow"),
    sf_mobility_educ_current_19 %>%
      group_by(education) %>%
      summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>%
      mutate(mobility = "Here this year")
  ) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = mobility,
    values_from = estimate
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    `External net` = Inflow - Outflow,
    `Internal net` = `Here this year` - `Here last year` - `External net`,
  ) %>%
  mutate(education =  factor(education, levels = c("Bachelor's degree","Graduate or professional degree","Some college or associate's degree","High school graduate (includes equivalency)","Less than high school graduate"))
  )%>%
  arrange(education) %>%
  select(
    `Educational attaintment` = education,
    `Internal net`,
    `External net`,
    `Here last year`,
    `Here this year`,
    Outflow,
    Inflow
  )

datatable(
  sf_flows_19, 
  rownames = FALSE,
  caption = htmltools::tags$caption(
    style = 'caption-side: bottom; text-align: center;',
    'Educational mobility in the San Francisco county')
  )

First, I assume that the high Internal net for the Less than High school graduate is mainly due to the new enrollments for young students. The Internal net values for the other educational attainment categories add up to a total of +570. As mentioned before, it is quite close to a break-even; the Bachelor degrees and High school graduate (includes equivalency) categories show a negative Internal net leading to a positive one for the Graduate or professional degree and Some college or associate’s degree. The fact that the Internal net is slightly higher than 0 might be due to several factors, such as a higher number of people answering the ACS in 2019 compared to 2018 and the previous years.

The External net is however extremely negative (-12,027 in total), especially among the Bachelor degrees (-6,881, representing more than 50% of the global leavings). Many reasons can lead to such a result. First, the high rent price of housing in the San Francisco county might force the students to live outside the county to pursue their studies there. Also, students willing to pursue higher level studies might suffer from a lack of educational institutions among the county, forcing them to move to an other one. Because the Bachelor degrees category is the one with the extreme negative External net value, I may conclude that it is mainly due to a a lack of educational institutions.

In fact, the San Francisco county is proportionally very small compared to its student population. Therefore, there are two possibilities: there is not enough place for every students willing to pursue higher level studies, or the reputation of the institutions is not good enough to attract the students. This last possibility is even more relevant because of the housing price in the county: high level studies are very expensive and time-consuming, so accumulate the tuition fees with a high rent could be impossible for a standard student.

    vars = c("group(B07409)")
  ) %>%
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>%
      select(name, label),
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>%
  select(-variable) %>%
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"mobility","education"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    mobility = ifelse(
      mobility %in% c("Same house:", "Moved within same county:"),
      "Here since last year",
      "Outflow"
    )
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(education)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, education) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))


ala_mobility_educ_current_18 <-
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "county:001",
    regionin = "state:06",

    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>%
      select(name, label),
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>%
  select(-variable) %>%
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"mobility","education"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    mobility = "Here last year"
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(education)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, education) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))


ala_flows_19 <-
  rbind(
    ala_mobility_educ_current_18,
    ala_mobility_educ_lastyear_19 %>%
      filter(mobility == "Outflow"),
    ala_mobility_educ_current_19 %>%
      filter(mobility == "Inflow"),
    ala_mobility_educ_current_19 %>%
      group_by(education) %>%
      summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>%
      mutate(mobility = "Here this year")
  ) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = mobility,
    values_from = estimate
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    `External net` = Inflow - Outflow,
    `Internal net` = `Here this year` - `Here last year` - `External net`,
  ) %>%
  mutate(education =  factor(education, levels = c("Bachelor's degree","Graduate or professional degree","Some college or associate's degree","High school graduate (includes equivalency)","Less than high school graduate"))
  )%>%
  arrange(education)%>%
  select(
    `Educational attaintment` = education,
    `Internal net`,
    `External net`,
    `Here last year`,
    `Here this year`,
    Outflow,
    Inflow
  )

datatable(
  ala_flows_19, 
  rownames = FALSE,
  caption = htmltools::tags$caption(
    style = 'caption-side: bottom; text-align: center;',
    'Educational mobility in the Alameda county')
  )

The situation is very different in the Alameda county. The Less than high school graduate category shows a negative Internal net, which means than the enrollment rate of new students is lower than the rate of students pursuing higher level studies. The high rate of K-12 students with no internet access at home mentioned in the previous part might explain the choices of the families to move out in order to enroll their young children in a place where they can get a better access to every source of education.

Both the High school graduate and Some college or associate’s degree categories’ Internal net are extremely negative (-7,992 and -8,890, which amounts to -16,882 in total), and the Graduate or professional degree and Bachelor’s degree categories’ Internal net are highly positive (+6,148 and +18,271, which amounts to +24,419 in total). Therefore, students in the Alameda county tend to graduate more than in the San Francisco county. The presence of UC Berkeley inside this county might explain why and support the argument of a lack of high level and affordable educational institutions in the San Francisco county.

To compare with the San Francisco county, I notice that the global Internal net for the categories other than Less than high school graduate adds up to +7,537. This is mainly due to the high Internal net for the Bachelor’s degree category. Reasons explaining that could be a high number of students coming in the county to pursue undergraduate studies and starting to fill the ACS as Alameda’s citizens only after they get their bachelor’s degree, or the filling of ACS by non-US citizens students coming to the county to pursue graduate study lasting more than one year or work for the second consecutive year in the county after they completed their undergraduate in a foreign country.

The External net is way more balanced than the Internal net. All categories considered, it amounts to +2,680. However, it does not mean that the county is attractive in terms of educational opportunities. Most of the positive External net is related to the Bachelor’s degree (+6,034) and Graduate or professional degree (+1,515) educational attainment categories. Yet, people with such an educational attainment tend more to settle to work than to pursue higher level studies. On the opposite, the categories more willing to pursue higher studies (Some college or associate’s degree and High school graduate) show negative numbers (respectively -6,028 and -15), which supports my argument.

Also, it is interesting to raise the issue of the Less than high school graduate category: while the Internal net is negative, the External net is positive. It means that the usual inhabitants of the Alameda county with less than a high school diploma as educational attainment tend to leave the county, while there are still newcomers with the same educational attainment. Because I assumed earlier that the departures should mean a low quality of learning access (cf. high percentage of K-12 students with no internet access at home), the arrivals could in fact prove that this poor access to learning tools might not be a generalized phenomenon in the county, but rather a localized issue. The data provided this approach are however not sufficient to give a proper answer to that question.

The Solano county shows interesting results, leading to the questioning of the relevance of this method of analysis of the educational mobility. In fact, despite a very low percentage of K-12 students with no internet access at home supposedly testifying an environment conductive to a good access to education, it appears to be a situation pretty similar to the Alameda county:

  • The Less than high school graduate, High school graduate and Some college or associate’s degree categories prompts negative Internal net values. While the values for the Less than high school graduate categories are quite similar for the Solano and Alameda counties (-1,301 against -1,305), they are less extreme for High school graduate and Some college or associate’s degree categories (-1,262 against -7,992, and -5,697 against -8,890). This means that the poor access to internet at home in the Alameda county is not the only issue leading to the departures of students: the lack of educational institutions is also very impacting. I have already raised this issue for the San Francisco county, thus the Solano county adds weight to it.
  • The Bachelor’s degree and Graduate or professional degree categories prompts positive Internal net values, but much lower (+2,346 against +18,271, and +2,711 against +6,148). Once again, this raise the issue of the lack of educational institution, because the high numbers in the Alameda county could be explained by the presence of huge universities such as UC Berkeley. Also, the Solano county does not suffer from high rent prices like the San Francisco county. Therefore, the economic factor should not weight much here.

When it comes to the External net values, these are higly positive (+5,020 net total) compared to the two other counties (+2,680 in the Alameda county and -12,027 in the San Francisco county).

Conclusion on educational mobility

This indicator is much limited by the scale of study. As mentioned for the Alameda county, studying the educational mobility at the scale of the county is not enough to understand the inequalities in the access to education. Also, as mentioned for the San Francisco county, other factors such as the global rent price of habitation are at stake when it comes to settle somewhere to pursue studies. Therefore, it is hard to come up with a solid conclusion with this indicator only. The same results in terms of Internal net and External net in two different counties might have very different interpretations and raise contrasted issues. However, it narrows down the real impact of the K-12 students with no internet access at home indicator; while having very good results with this indicator, the Solano county appeared not to be attractive for educational attaintment categories usually aiming at pursuing higher level studies. This means that the proficiency and quality of educational instutions in the county is also a crucial factor in the choice of residential location to reach an higher educational attaintment, a phenomenon I raised in my San Francisco county educational mobility analyzis.

Also, it is hard to come up with any conclusion regarding a potential relation between educational mobility and race with these data only. Racial, social and access to education inequalities have proven to be much correlated with the perspective given by the two first indicators, but once again it is hard to come up with any tangible conclusion with the data on educational mobility. The study at a county scale is too general to give a proper insight on the reason of the arrivals/departures in a county, and neglicts the differences in access to education among a county.
